# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: uikit-ios
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:uikit-ios/cocoa-touch] UIKit provides an abstraction layer of iOS, the operating system for the iPhone, iPod Touch, and iPad.
[src:uikit-ios/cocoa-touch] UIKit is similar to AppKit from the macOS Cocoa API toolset, and it too is primarily written in the Objective-C language.
[src:uikit-ios/cocoa-touch] UIKit allows the use of hardware and features that are not found in macOS computers and are thus unique to the iOS range of devices.
[src:uikit-ios/cocoa-touch] Like AppKit, UIKit follows a Model–View–Controller (MVC) software architecture.
[src:uikit-ios/cocoa-touch] UIKit contains a different set of graphical control elements from AppKit.
[src:uikit-ios/cocoa-touch] Tools for developing applications based on UIKit are included in the iOS SDK.
[src:uikit-ios/cocoa-touch] iOS, watchOS, and tvOS technologies can be seen as a set of layers, with UIKit at the highest level and the core operating system / kernel at the bottom.
[src:uikit-ios/cocoa-touch] UIKit provides the key frameworks for developing applications on devices running iOS, and is based atop Foundation Kit.
[src:uikit-ios/cocoa-touch] Microsoft's WinObjC, the GNUstep-based iOS bridge for the Universal Windows Platform, contains working implementations of frameworks such as Foundation, UIKit, and MapKit released under the MIT License.
[src:uikit-ios/cocoa-touch] One of the UIKit implementations is based on XAML.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] In computer programming, **event-driven programming** is a programming paradigm in which the flow of the program is determined by external events.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] User interface (UI) events from keyboards and mice, touchpads and touchscreens, and external sensor inputs are common cases.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] Events may also be programmatically generated, such as from messages from other programs, notifications from other threads, or other network events.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programming is the dominant paradigm used in graphical user interface (GUI) applications and network servers.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] In an event-driven application, there is generally an event loop that listens for events and then triggers a callback function when one of those events is detected.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programs can be written in any programming language, although the task is easier in languages that provide high-level abstractions.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] Although they do not exactly fit the event-driven model, interrupt handling and exception handling have many similarities.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] It is important to differentiate between event-driven and message-driven (aka queue-driven) paradigms: event-driven services (e.g.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] AWS SNS) are decoupled from their consumers, whereas message/queue-driven services (e.g.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] AWS SQS) are coupled with their consumers.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] Because the event loop that retrieves and dispatches events is common amongst applications, many programming frameworks provide an implementation of an event loop, and the application developer only needs to write the event handlers.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] The actual logic is contained in event handler routines.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] These routines handle the events to which the main program will respond.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] For example, a single mouse-click on a "Save" command button in a GUI program might trigger a routine to save data to a database.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] An "Exit" button might trigger a routine to exit the program.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] The event loop receives events from all such command buttons and other GUI elements, dispatching the appropriate event handler routine for each button.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] Event handler routines need to be bound to specific events, so the event loop can dispatch the correct routine in response to the event.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] Many IDEs simplify this process by providing the programmer with an event handling template for each specific event (such as a button click), allowing the programmer to focus on writing the event-handling code.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] In a sequential program, keeping track of execution order and history is normally trivial.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] But in an event-driven program, event handlers execute non-sequentially in response to external events.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] Special attention and planning is required to correctly structure the event handlers to work when called in any order.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] Most existing GUI architectures use event-driven programming.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] The Java AWT framework processes all UI changes on a single thread, called the Event dispatching thread.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] Similarly, all UI updates in the Java framework JavaFX occur on the JavaFX Application Thread.
[src:uikit-ios/event-driven-programming] Most network servers and frameworks such as Node.js are also event-driven.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] As of December 2023, Apple's App Store contains more than 3.8 million iOS mobile apps.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Like macOS, it includes components of the Mach microkernel and FreeBSD.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Although some parts of iOS are open source under the Apple Public Source License and other licenses, iOS is proprietary software.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In 2005, when Steve Jobs began planning the iPhone, he stated that he had a choice to either "shrink the Mac, which would be an epic feat of engineering, or enlarge the iPod".
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Jobs favored the former approach but pitted the Macintosh and iPod teams, led by Scott Forstall and Tony Fadell, respectively, against each other in an internal competition, with Forstall winning by creating iPhone OS.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The decision enabled the success of the iPhone as a platform for third-party developers: using a well-known desktop operating system as its basis allowed the many third-party Mac developers to write software for the iPhone with minimal retraining.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Forstall was also responsible for creating a software development kit for programmers to build iPhone apps, as well as an App Store within iTunes.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The operating system was unveiled with the iPhone at the Macworld Conference & Expo on January 9, 2007, and released in June of that year.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] At the time of its unveiling in January, Steve Jobs claimed: "iPhone runs OS X" and runs "desktop class applications", but at the time of the iPhone's release, the operating system was renamed "iPhone OS".
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Initially, third-party native applications were not supported.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Jobs' reasoning was that developers could build web applications through the Safari web browser that "would behave like native apps on the iPhone".
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In October 2007, Apple announced that a native software development kit (SDK) was under development and that they planned to put it "in developers' hands in February".
[src:uikit-ios/ios] On March 6, 2008, Apple held a press event, announcing the iPhone SDK.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The iOS App Store was opened on July 10, 2008, with an initial 500 applications available.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] As of March 2016, 1 million apps are natively compatible with the iPad tablet computer.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] These apps have collectively been downloaded more than 130 billion times.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] App intelligence firm Sensor Tower estimated that the App Store would reach 5 million apps by 2020.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In September 2007, Apple announced the iPod Touch, a redesigned iPod based on the iPhone form factor.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It also includes a mobile version of Safari for web browsing, as well as access to the App Store, iTunes Library, iBookstore, Contacts, and Notes.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Content is downloadable via Wi-Fi and optional 3G service or synced through the user's computer.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] AT&T was initially the sole U.S. provider of 3G wireless access for the iPad.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In June 2010, Apple rebranded iPhone OS as "iOS".
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The trademark "IOS" had been used by Cisco for over a decade for its operating system, IOS, used on its routers.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] To avoid any potential lawsuit, Apple licensed the "IOS" trademark from Cisco.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The Apple Watch smartwatch was announced by Tim Cook on September 9, 2014, being introduced as a product with health and fitness-tracking.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It uses watchOS as its operating system; watchOS is based on iOS, with new features created specially for the Apple Watch such as an activity tracking app.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In October 2016, Apple opened its first iOS Developer Academy in Naples inside University of Naples Federico II's new campus.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The course is completely free, aimed at acquiring specific technical skills on the creation and management of applications for the Apple ecosystem platforms.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] At the academy there are also issues of business administration (business planning and business management with a focus on digital opportunities) and there is a path dedicated to the design of graphical interfaces.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Students have the opportunity to participate in the "Enterprise Track", an in-depth training experience on the entire life cycle of an app, from design to implementation, to security, troubleshooting, data storage and cloud usage.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] As of 2020, the academy graduated almost a thousand students from all over the world, who have worked on 400 app ideas and have already published about 50 apps on the iOS App Store.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In the 2018–2019 academic year, students from more than 30 countries arrived.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] 35 of these have been selected to attend the Worldwide Developer Conference, the annual Apple Developer Conference held annually in California in early June.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] On June 3, 2019, iPadOS, the branded version of iOS for iPad, was announced during the WWDC 2019 keynote; it was launched on September 25, 2019.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] On June 9, 2025, at WWDC 2025, Apple introduced iOS 26.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The version number indicates the year following the year in which the version was introduced; this numbering scheme is now being used for all Apple operating systems, keeping their version numbers synchronized.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] On June 8, 2026, at WWDC 2026, Apple introduced iOS 27.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It introduces Siri AI, a new model designed by Apple in collaboration with Google.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Siri AI is able to handle significantly more complex tasks, such as making shortcuts in the Shortcuts app and planning advanced routes.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The revamped Siri is similar to an AI chatbot, and it will receive an app where users can look at their past conversations.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The iOS user interface is based upon direct manipulation, using multi-touch gestures such as *swipe*, *tap*, *pinch*, and *reverse pinch*.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Interface control elements include sliders, switches, and buttons.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Internal accelerometers are used by some applications to respond to shaking the device (one common result is the undo command) or rotating it in three dimensions (one common result is switching between portrait and landscape mode).
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Various accessibility described in § Accessibility functions enable users with vision and hearing disabilities to properly use iOS.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The lock screen shows the time and a user's lock screen widgets, which display timely information from apps.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The lock screen also has two buttons, called Controls, which are only available on iPhone.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] These default to flashlight and camera, but they can be customized to any control available in Control Center and can also be removed.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Along the top of the screen is a status bar, showing information about the device and its connectivity.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It is possible to manage brightness, volume, wireless connections, music player, etc.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Scrolling from the top left to the bottom (or top to bottom on iPhones with Touch ID) will open the Notification Center, which in the latest versions of iOS is very similar to the lock screen.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It displays notifications in chronological order and groups them by application.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] From the notifications of some apps it is possible to interact directly, for example by replying to a message directly from it.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Both can be found in the Notification Center, and show for a set amount of time on the lock screen (unless the user has Notification Center allowed when locked).
[src:uikit-ios/ios] On iPhones with Touch ID, screenshots can be created with the simultaneous press of the home and power buttons.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In comparison to Android, which requires the buttons to be held down, a short press does suffice on iOS.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] On iPhone with Face ID, screenshots are captured using the volume-up and power buttons instead.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The camera application used a skeuomorphic closing camera shutter animation prior to iOS 7.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Since then, it uses a simple short blackout effect.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Some camera settings such as video resolution and frame rate are not adjustable through the camera interface itself, but are outsourced to the system settings.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] A new feature in iOS 13 called "context menus" shows related actions when you touch and hold an item.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] When the context menu is displayed, the background is blurred.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] To choose from a few options, a selection control is used.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Selectors can appear anchored at the bottom or in line with the content (called date selectors).
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Date selectors take on the appearance of any other selection control, but with a column for day, month, and optionally year.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Alerts appear in the center of the screen, but there are also alerts that scroll up from the bottom of the screen (called "action panels").
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Destructive actions (such as eliminating any element) are colored red.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The official font of iOS is San Francisco.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It is designed for small text readability, and is used throughout the operating system, including third-party apps.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The icons are 180x180px in size for iPhones with a larger screen, usually models over 6 inches, including iPhone 11 Pro and iPhone 8 Plus, while they are 120x120px on iPhones with smaller displays.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The home screen appears whenever the user unlocks the device, presses the physical "Home" button while in an app, or swipes up from the bottom of the screen using the home bar.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The screen has a status bar across the top to display data, such as time, battery level, and signal strength.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The rest of the screen is devoted to the current application.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] When a passcode is set and a user switches on the device, the passcode must be entered at the Lock Screen before access to the Home screen is granted.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In iPhone OS 3, Spotlight was introduced, allowing users to search media, apps, emails, contacts, messages, reminders, calendar events, and similar content.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In iOS 7 and later, Spotlight is accessed by pulling down anywhere on the home screen (except for the top and bottom edges that open Notification Center and Control Center).
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In iOS 9, there are two ways to access Spotlight.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] As with iOS 7 and 8, pulling down on any homescreen will show Spotlight.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] However, it can also be accessed as it was in iOS versions 3 through 6.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] This endows Spotlight with Siri suggestions, which include app suggestions, contact suggestions and news.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In iOS 10, Spotlight is at the top of the now-dedicated "Today" panel.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] With the release of iPhone OS 3.2, users gained the ability to set a wallpaper for the Home Screen.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] iOS 7 introduced a parallax effect on the Home Screen, which shifts the device's wallpaper and icons in response to the movement of the device, creating a 3D effect and an illusion of floating icons.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] This effect is also visible in the tab view of Mail and Safari.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Researchers found that users organize icons on their homescreens based on usage frequency and relatedness of the applications, as well as for reasons of usability and aesthetics.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] iOS originally used Helvetica as the system font.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Apple switched to Helvetica Neue exclusively for the iPhone 4 and its Retina Display, and retained Helvetica as the system font for older iPhone devices on iOS 4.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] With iOS 7, Apple announced that they would change the system font to Helvetica Neue Light, a decision that sparked criticism for inappropriate usage of a light, thin typeface for low-resolution mobile screens.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Apple eventually chose Helvetica Neue instead.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The release of iOS 7 also introduced the ability to scale text or apply other forms of text accessibility changes through Settings.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] With iOS 9, Apple changed the font to San Francisco, an Apple-designed font aimed at maximum legibility and font consistency across its product lineup.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] iOS 4 introduced folders, which can be created by dragging an application on top of another, and from then on, more items can be added to the folder using the same procedure.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] A title for the folder is automatically selected by the category of applications inside, but the name can also be edited by the user.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] When apps inside folders receive notification badges, the individual numbers of notifications are added up and the total number is displayed as a notification badge on the folder itself.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Originally, folders on an iPhone could include up to 12 apps, while folders on iPad could include 20.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] With increasing display sizes on newer iPhone hardware, iOS 7 updated the folders with pages similar to the home screen layout, allowing for a significant expansion of folder functionality.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Each page of a folder can contain up to nine apps, and there can be 15 pages in total, allowing for a total of 135 apps in a single folder.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In iOS 9, Apple updated folder sizes for iPad hardware, allowing for 16 apps per page, still at 15 pages maximum, increasing the total to 240 apps.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Before iOS 5, notifications were delivered in a modal window and could not be viewed after being dismissed.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In iOS 5, Apple introduced Notification Center, which allows users to view a history of notifications.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The user can tap a notification to open its corresponding app, or clear it.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Notifications are now delivered in banners that appear briefly at the top of the screen.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] If a user taps a received notification, the application that sent the notification will be opened.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Users can also choose to view notifications in modal alert windows by adjusting the application's notification settings.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Introduced with iOS 8, widgets are now accessible through the Notification Center, defined by 3rd parties.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] When an app sends a notification while closed, a red badge appears on its icon.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] This badge tells the user, at a glance, how many notifications that app has sent.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] iOS devices come with preinstalled apps developed by Apple including Mail, Maps, TV, Music, FaceTime, Wallet, Health, and many more.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Applications ("apps") are the most general form of application software that can be installed on iOS.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] They are downloaded from the official catalog of the App Store digital store, where apps are subjected to security checks before being made available to users.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In June 2017, Apple updated its guidelines to specify that app developers will no longer have the ability to use custom prompts for encouraging users to leave reviews for their apps.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] IOS applications can also be installed directly from an IPA file provided by the software distributor, via unofficial ways.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] They are written using iOS Software Development Kit (SDK) and, often, combined with Xcode, using officially supported programming languages, including Swift and Objective-C.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Other companies have also created tools that allow for the development of native iOS apps using their respective programming languages.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Applications for iOS are mostly built using components of UIKit, a programming framework.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It allows applications to have a consistent look and feel with the OS, nevertheless offering customization.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Elements automatically update along with iOS updates, automatically including new interface rules.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] UIKit elements are very adaptable, this allows developers to design a single app that looks the same on any iOS device.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In addition to defining the iOS interface, UIKit defines the functionality of the application.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] At first, Apple did not intend to release an SDK to developers, because they did not want third-party apps to be developed for iOS, building web apps instead.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] However, this technology never entered into common use, this led Apple to change its opinion, so in October 2007 the SDK for developers was announced, finally released on March 6, 2008.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The SDK includes an inclusive set of development tools, including an audio mixer and an iPhone simulator.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It is not available for Microsoft Windows PCs.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] To test the application, get technical support, and distribute applications through App Store, developers are required to subscribe to the Apple Developer Program.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Over the years, the Apple Store apps surpassed multiple major milestones, including 50,000, 100,000, 250,000, 500,000, 1 million, and 2 million apps.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The billionth application was installed on April 24, 2009.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] App Library automatically categorizes apps into folders based on their function or type and includes an alphabetical list of all installed apps.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] For example, it might group all social media apps into one folder and productivity apps into another.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Users can quickly find and access apps by using the search bar at the top of the App Library.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Users can choose to hide specific app pages from the home screen, making it easier to focus on the apps they use most frequently.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] iOS enforces strict sandboxing to maintain security and privacy.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Apps are generally limited to accessing their own containers and specific system-provided directories, such as the Photos library.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] To access files outside of their sandbox, iOS uses mechanisms like document pickers, file providers, and app extensions.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] iOS 8 introduced the Document Picker and Document Provider extensions as part of the document interaction controller.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] This allows apps to open, save, and interact with documents stored in a central location or cloud storage services.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] With iOS 11, Apple introduced the Files app and the File Provider extension, providing a central location for users to manage and organize their files.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Apps can integrate with the Files app to make their documents accessible and editable directly from the Files app.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] These files can be accessed across multiple devices as long as the user is signed in with the same Apple ID.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] iOS offers various accessibility features to help users with vision and hearing disabilities.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] One major feature, VoiceOver, provides a voice reading information on the screen, including contextual buttons, icons, links and other user interface elements, and allows the user to navigate the operating system through gestures.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Any apps with default controls and developed with a UIKit framework gets VoiceOver functionality built in.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] One example includes holding up the iPhone to take a photo, with VoiceOver describing the photo scenery.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] As part of a "Made for iPhone" program, introduced with the release of iOS 7 in 2013, Apple has developed technology to use Bluetooth and a special technology protocol to let compatible third-party equipment connect with iPhones and iPads for streaming audio directly to a user's ears.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Additional customization available for Made for iPhone products include battery tracking and adjustable sound settings for different environments.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Building into the core of our products supports a vision of an inclusive world where opportunity and access to information are barrier-free, empowering individuals with disabilities to achieve their goals".
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Criticism has been aimed at iOS depending on both internet connection (either WiFi or through iTunes) and a working SIM card upon first activation.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] This restriction has been loosened in iOS 12, which no longer requires the latter.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Multitasking for iOS was first released in June 2010 along with the release of iOS 4.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Only certain devices—iPhone 4, iPhone 3GS, and iPod Touch 3rd generation—were able to multitask.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The iPad did not get multitasking until iOS 4.2.1 in that November.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The implementation of multitasking in iOS has been criticized for its approach, which limits the work that applications in the background can perform to a limited function set and requires application developers to add explicit support for it.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Before iOS 4, multitasking was limited to a selection of the applications Apple included on the device.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Users could however "jailbreak" their device in order to unofficially multitask.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In iOS 7, Apple introduced a new multitasking feature, providing all apps with the ability to perform background updates.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] This feature prefers to update the user's most frequently used apps and prefers to use Wi-Fi networks over a cellular network, without markedly reducing the device's battery life.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In iOS 4.0 to iOS 6.x, double-clicking the home button activates the application switcher.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] A scrollable dock-style interface appears from the bottom, moving the contents of the screen up.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Choosing an icon switches to an application.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] To the far left are icons which function as music controls, a rotation lock, and on iOS 4.2 and above, a volume controller.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] With the introduction of iOS 7, double-clicking the home button also activates the application switcher.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] However, unlike previous versions it displays screenshots of open applications on top of the icon and horizontal scrolling allows for browsing through previous apps, and it is possible to close applications by dragging them up, similar to how WebOS handled multiple cards.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Now, instead of the home screen appearing at the leftmost of the application switcher, it appears rightmost.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In iOS 11, the application switcher receives a major redesign.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In the iPad, the Control Center and app switcher are combined.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The app switcher in the iPad can also be accessed by swiping up from the bottom.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In the iPhone, the app switcher cannot be accessed if there are no apps in the RAM.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In iOS 4.0 to iOS 6.x, briefly holding the icons in the application switcher makes them "jiggle" (similarly to the homescreen) and allows the user to *force* quit the applications by tapping the red minus circle that appears at the corner of the app's icon.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Clearing applications from multitasking stayed the same from iOS 4.0 through 6.1.6, the last version of iOS 6.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] As of iOS 7, the process has become faster and easier.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In iOS 7, instead of holding the icons to close them, they are closed by simply swiping them upwards off the screen.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Up to three apps can be cleared at a time compared to one in versions up to iOS 6.1.6.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Task completion allows apps to continue a certain task after the app has been suspended.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] As of iOS 4.0, apps can request up to ten minutes to complete a task in the background.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] This doesn't extend to background uploads and downloads though (e.g. if a user starts a download in one application, it won't finish if they switch away from the application).
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Siri (/ˈsɪri/) is a virtual assistant integrated into iOS.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The assistant uses voice queries and a natural-language user interface to answer questions, make recommendations, and perform actions by delegating requests to a set of Internet services.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The software adapts to users' individual language usages, searches, and preferences, with continuing use.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Originally released as an app for iOS in February 2010, it was acquired by Apple two months later, and then integrated into iPhone 4S at its release in October 2011.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] At that time, the separate app was also removed from the iOS App Store.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Siri supports a wide range of user commands, including performing phone actions, checking basic information, scheduling events and reminders, handling device settings, searching the Internet, navigating areas, finding information on entertainment, and is able to engage with iOS-integrated apps.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] With the release of iOS 10 in 2016, Apple opened up limited third-party access to Siri, including third-party messaging apps, as well as payments, ride-sharing, and Internet calling apps.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Game Center is an online multiplayer "social gaming network" released by Apple.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It allows users to "invite friends to play a game, start a multiplayer game through matchmaking, track their achievements, and compare their high scores on a leaderboard." iOS 5 and above adds support for profile photos.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Game Center was announced during an iOS 4 preview event hosted by Apple on April 8, 2010.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] A preview was released to registered Apple developers in August.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It was released on September 8, 2010, with iOS 4.1 on iPhone 4, iPhone 3GS, and iPod Touch 2nd generation through 4th generation.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Game Center made its public debut on the iPad with iOS 4.2.1.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] There is no support for the iPhone 3G, original iPhone and the first-generation iPod Touch (the latter two devices did not have Game Center because they did not get iOS 4).
[src:uikit-ios/ios] However, Game Center is unofficially available on the iPhone 3G via a hack.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The instruction set architectures supported by iOS are the ARM architectures.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] iOS powers almost exclusively Apple hardware.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It is used for all iPhones and iPod Touch devices.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Further, Apple Watches, Apple TVs, and iPads either also use iOS for some models or use OSes based on iOS for other models.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The iOS software development kit (SDK) allows for the development of mobile apps that can run on iOS.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] While originally developing iPhone prior to its unveiling in 2007, Apple's then-CEO Steve Jobs did not intend to let third-party developers build native apps for iOS, instead directing them to make web applications for the Safari web browser.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] However, backlash from developers prompted the company to reconsider, with Jobs announcing in October 2007 that Apple would have a software development kit available for developers by February 2008.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The SDK is a free download for users of Mac personal computers.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The SDK contains sets giving developers access to various functions and services of iOS devices, such as hardware and software attributes.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It also contains an iPhone simulator to mimic the look and feel of the device on the computer while developing.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] New versions of the SDK accompany new versions of iOS.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In order to test applications, get technical support, and distribute apps through App Store, developers are required to subscribe to the Apple Developer Program.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Combined with Xcode, the iOS SDK helps developers write iOS apps using officially supported programming languages, including Swift and Objective-C.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Apple provides major updates to the iOS operating system annually.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Since iOS 5, the primary method of delivery has been over-the-air.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Updates are also available using iTunes on older versions of macOS and Windows, using Finder on macOS starting with macOS Catalina, and using the Apple Devices app on Windows starting with Windows 10 version 22H2.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The device checks an XML-based PLIST file on mesu.apple.com for updates.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Updates are delivered as unencrypted ZIP files.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Updates are checked for regularly, and are downloaded and installed automatically if enabled.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Otherwise, the user can install them manually or are prompted to allow automatic installation overnight if plugged in and connected to Wi-Fi.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] iPod Touch users originally had to pay for system software updates due to accounting rules that designated it not a "subscription device" like the iPhone or Apple TV, causing many iPod Touch owners not to update.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In September 2009, a change in accounting rules won tentative approval, affecting Apple's earnings and stock price, and allowing iPod Touch updates to be delivered free of charge.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Apple significantly extended the cycle of updates for iOS-supported devices over the years.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The iPhone (1st generation) and iPhone 3G only received two major iOS updates, while later models had support for three to seven major updates.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] iOS uses the XNU kernel included in the Darwin operating system and used by macOS, adapted to work with devices that run iOS.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Since its initial release, iOS has been subject to a variety of different hacks centered around adding functionality not allowed by Apple.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Prior to the 2008 debut of Apple's native iOS App Store, the primary motive for jailbreaking was to bypass Apple's purchase mechanism for installing the App Store's native applications.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Apple claimed that it would not release iOS software updates designed specifically to break these tools (other than applications that perform SIM unlocking); however, with each subsequent iOS update, previously un-patched jailbreak exploits are usually patched.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] When a device is booting, it loads Apple's own kernel initially, so a jailbroken device must be exploited and have the kernel patched each time it is booted up.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] An *untethered* jailbreak uses exploits that are powerful enough to allow the user to turn their device off and back on at will, with the device starting up completely, and the kernel will be patched without the help of a computer – in other words, it will be jailbroken even after each reboot.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] A tethered jailbreak is only able to temporarily jailbreak the device during a single boot.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] If the user turns the device off and then boots it back up without the help of a jailbreak tool, the device will no longer be running a patched kernel, and it may get stuck in a partially started state, such as Recovery Mode.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In order for the device to start completely and with a patched kernel, it must be "re-jailbroken" with a computer (using the "boot tethered" feature of a tool) each time it is turned on.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] All changes to the files on the device (such as installed package files or edited system files) will persist between reboots, including changes that can only function if the device is jailbroken (such as installed package files).
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In more recent years, two other solutions have been created – *semi-tethered* and *semi-untethered*.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] A semi-tethered solution is one where the device is able to start up on its own, but it will no longer have a patched kernel, and therefore will not be able to run modified code.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] It will, however, still be usable for normal functions, just like stock iOS.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] To start with a patched kernel, the user must start the device with the help of the jailbreak tool.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] A semi-untethered jailbreak gives the ability to start the device on its own.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] On first boot, the device will not be running a patched kernel.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] However, rather than having to run a tool from a computer to apply the kernel patches, the user is able to re-jailbreak their device with the help of an app (usually sideloaded using Cydia Impactor) running on their device.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In the case of the iOS 9.2-9.3.3 and 64-bit 10.x jailbreaks, Safari-based exploits were available, thereby meaning websites could be used to re-jailbreak.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In more detail: Each iOS device has a bootchain that tries to make sure only trusted/signed code is loaded.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] A device with a tethered jailbreak is able to boot up with the help of a jailbreaking tool because the tool executes exploits via USB that bypass parts of that "chain of trust", bootstrapping to a pwned (no signature check) iBEC, or iBoot to finish the boot process.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Since the arrival of Apple's native iOS App Store, and—along with it—third-party applications, the general motives for jailbreaking have changed.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] People jailbreak for many different reasons, including gaining filesystem access, installing custom device themes, and modifying SpringBoard.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] An additional motivation is that it may enable the installation of pirated apps.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] On some devices, jailbreaking also makes it possible to install alternative operating systems, such as Android and the Linux kernel.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Primarily, users jailbreak their devices because of the limitations of iOS.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Depending on the method used, the effects of jailbreaking may be permanent or temporary.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In 2010, the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF) successfully convinced the U.S.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Copyright Office to allow an exemption to the general prohibition on circumvention of copyright protection systems under the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA).
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The exemption allows jailbreaking of iPhones for the sole purpose of allowing legally obtained applications to be added to the iPhone.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The exemption does not affect the contractual relations between Apple and an iPhone owner, for example, jailbreaking voiding the iPhone warranty; however, it is solely based on Apple's discretion on whether they will fix jailbroken devices in the event that they need to be repaired.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] At the same time, the Copyright Office exempted unlocking an iPhone from DMCA's anticircumvention prohibitions.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Unlocking an iPhone allows the iPhone to be used with any wireless carrier using the same GSM or CDMA technology for which the particular phone model was designed to operate.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Initially most wireless carriers in the US did not allow iPhone owners to unlock it for use with other carriers.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] However AT&T allowed iPhone owners who had satisfied contract requirements to unlock their iPhone.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Instructions to unlock the device are available from Apple, but it is ultimately at the sole discretion of the carrier to authorize unlocking the device.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] This allows the use of a carrier-sourced iPhone on other networks.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Modern versions of iOS and the iPhone fully support LTE across multiple carriers wherever the phone was purchased.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Programs to remove SIM lock restrictions are available, but are not supported by Apple, and most often not a permanent unlock – a soft unlock, which modifies the iPhone so that the baseband will accept the SIM card of any GSM carrier.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] SIM unlocking is not jailbreaking, but a jailbreak is also required for these unofficial software unlocks.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] The legality of software unlocking varies in each country; for example, in the US, there is a DMCA exemption for unofficial software unlocking of devices purchased before January 26, 2013.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Competitor Microsoft, via a PR spokesman, criticized Apple's control over its platform.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Particularly at issue is the ability for Apple to remotely disable or delete apps at will.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Some in the tech community have expressed concern that the locked-down iOS represents a growing trend in Apple's approach to computing, particularly Apple's shift away from machines that hobbyists can "tinker with" and note the potential for such restrictions to stifle software innovation.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Former Facebook developer Joe Hewitt protested against Apple's control over its hardware as a "horrible precedent" but praised iOS's sandboxing of apps.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] iOS utilizes many security features in both hardware and software.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] iOS is the second most popular mobile operating system in the world, after Android.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Sales of iPads in recent years are also behind Android, while, by web use (a proxy for all use), iPads (using iOS) are still the most popular.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] At WWDC 2014, Tim Cook said 800 million devices had been sold by June 2014.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] During Apple's quarterly earnings call in January 2015, the company announced that they had sold over one billion iOS devices since 2007.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] By February 2023, there were 2 billion devices activated, and 1.5 billion iPhones had been sold since 2007.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] By late 2011, iOS accounted for 60% of the market share for smartphones and tablets.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] By the end of 2014, iOS accounted for 14.8% of the smartphone market and 27.6% of the tablet and two-in-one market.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In May 2023, StatCounter reported iOS was used on 31.44% of smartphones and 55.75% of tablets worldwide, measured by internet usage instead of sales.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] In the third quarter of 2015, research from Strategy Analytics showed that iOS adoption of the worldwide smartphone market was at a record low 12.1%, attributed to lackluster performance in China and Africa.
[src:uikit-ios/ios] Android accounted for 87.5% of the market, with Windows Phone and BlackBerry accounting for the rest.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:uikit-ios/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] A **storyboard** is a graphic organizer that consists of simple illustrations or images displayed in sequence for the purpose of pre-visualizing a motion picture, animation, motion graphic or interactive media sequence.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The storyboarding process, in its modern form, was developed at Walt Disney Productions during the early 1930s, after several years of similar processes being in use at Walt Disney and other animation studios.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Most early filmmakers shot their films like a play, with a fixed camera in a wide shot.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] In the first decades of the 20th century, with the development of new film techniques, such as camera movement and cutting, many filmmakers began to find pre-planning with artists' sketches to be useful.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Artists would sketch out ideas for gags or design sets, but at first these were largely conceptual.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Many large budget silent films were storyboarded, but most of this material has been lost during the reduction of the studio archives during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Special effects pioneer Georges Méliès is known to have been among the first filmmakers to use storyboards and pre-production art to visualize planned effects.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] However, storyboarding in the form widely known today was developed at the Walt Disney studio during the early 1930s.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Up to this point, every animator was assigned a scene and had to come up with gags around a theme with no regard to how they worked as part of a narrative.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] In the biography of her father, *The Story of Walt Disney* (Henry Holt, 1956), Diane Disney Miller explains that the first complete storyboards were created for the 1933 Disney short *Three Little Pigs*.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] According to Christopher Finch in *The Art of Walt Disney* (1995), Disney credited animator Webb Smith with creating the idea of drawing scenes on separate sheets of paper and pinning them up on a bulletin board to tell a story in sequence, thus creating the first storyboard.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] According to Pete Docter and Don Peri in *Directing at Disney* (2024), Dick Huemer credited Ted Sears with first inventing the storyboard while he was working at Fleischer Studios, but that studio was uninterested.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Sears then switched to working for Walt Disney Productions and introduced the storyboard to Walt Disney, who promptly understood its importance.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The second studio to switch from "story sketches" to storyboards was Walter Lantz Productions in early 1935; by 1936, Harman-Ising and Leon Schlesinger Productions also followed suit.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] By 1937 or 1938, all American animation studios were using storyboards.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Storyboarding became popular in live-action film production during the early 1940s and grew into a standard medium for the previsualization of films.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Pace Gallery curator Annette Michelson, writing of the exhibition *Drawing into Film: Director's Drawings*, considered the 1940s to 1990s to be the period in which "production design was largely characterized by the adoption of the storyboard".
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Storyboards are now an essential part of the creative process.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] A film storyboard (sometimes referred to as a shooting board), is essentially a series of frames, with drawings of the sequence of events in a film, similar to a comic book of the film or some section of the film produced beforehand.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] It helps film directors, cinematographers and television commercial advertising clients visualize the scenes and find potential problems before they occur.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Besides this, storyboards also help estimate the cost of the overall production and save time.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] A storyboard can also be helpful with the first stage of the film editing process, when the film editor is trying to assemble a rough cut to show to the director.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Often storyboards include arrows or instructions that indicate movement.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] For fast-paced action scenes, monochrome line art might suffice.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] For slower-paced dramatic films with an emphasis on lighting, color impressionist style art might be necessary.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] In creating a motion picture with any degree of fidelity to a script, a storyboard provides a visual layout of events as they are to be seen through the camera lens.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Storyboard frames are traditionally drawn on rectangles with the same aspect ratio as the video format in which the film will be shot.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] In the case of interactive media, it is the layout and sequence in which the user or viewer sees the content or information.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] In the storyboarding process, most technical details involved in crafting a film or interactive media project can be efficiently presented either in pictorial form in a storyboard frame, or as notes in the margins of specific frames.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] During principal photography for live-action films, scenes are rarely shot in the sequence in which they occur in the script.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] It is also sometimes necessary to film individual shots within a scene out of order and on different days, which can be very confusing.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] (The reasons for this are explained at length in the production board article.) In the latter scenario, directors can use storyboards on set to quickly refresh their memory as to the desired effect when those shots are later edited together in the correct order.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] This is more efficient than having to reread the script for each shot (with cast and crew waiting) to refresh their memory as to how they originally visualized they would film that shot.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] A common misconception is that storyboards are not used in theatre.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Directors and playwrights frequently use storyboards as special tools to understand the layout of the scene.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The great Russian theatre practitioner Stanislavski developed storyboards in his detailed production plans for his Moscow Art Theatre performances (such as of Chekhov's *The Seagull* in 1898).
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] In animation and special effects work, the storyboarding stage may be followed by simplified mock-ups called "animatics" to give a better idea of how a scene will look and feel with motion and timing.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] This allows the animators and directors to work out any screenplay, camera positioning, shot list, and timing issues that may exist with the current storyboard.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The storyboard and soundtrack are amended if necessary, and a new animatic may be created and reviewed by the production staff until the storyboard is finalized.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Editing at the animatic stage can help a production avoid wasting time and resources on the animation of scenes that would otherwise be edited out of the film at a later stage.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] A few minutes of screen time in traditional animation usually equates to months of work for a team of traditional animators, who must draw and paint a large amount of frames, meaning that all that labor will have to be written off if the finished scene does not work in the film's final cut.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] In the context of computer animation, storyboarding helps minimize the construction of unnecessary scene components and models, just as it helps live-action filmmakers evaluate what portions of sets need not be constructed because they will never come into the frame.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Often storyboards are animated with simple zooms and pans to simulate camera movement (using non-linear editing software).
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] These animations can be combined with available animatics, sound effects, and dialog to create a presentation of how a film could be shot and cut together.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Some feature film DVD *special features* include production animatics, which may have scratch vocals or may even feature vocals from the actual cast (usually where the scene was cut after the vocal recording phase but before the animation production phase).
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Animatics are also used by advertising agencies to create inexpensive test commercials.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] A variation, the "rip-o-matic", is made from scenes of existing movies, television programs or commercials, to simulate the look and feel of the proposed commercial.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Rip, in this sense, refers to ripping-off an original work to create a new one.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] A photomatic (probably derived from 'animatic' or photo-animation) is a series of still photographs edited together and presented on screen in a sequence.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Sound effects, voice-overs, and a soundtrack are added to the piece to show how a film could be shot and cut together.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Increasingly used by advertisers and advertising agencies to research the effectiveness of their proposed storyboard before committing to a 'full up' television advertisement.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The photomatic is usually a research tool, similar to an animatic, in that it represents the work to a test audience so that the commissioners of the work can gauge its effectiveness.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Originally, photographs were taken using a color negative film.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] A selection would be made from contact sheets and prints made.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The prints would be placed on a rostrum and recorded to videotape using a standard video camera.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Any moves, pans or zooms would have to be made in-camera.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The captured scenes could then be edited.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Digital photography, web access to stock photography and non-linear editing programs have had a marked impact on this way of filmmaking also leading to the term 'digimatic'.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Images can be shot and edited very quickly to allow important creative decisions to be made 'live'.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Photo composite animations can build intricate scenes that would normally be beyond many test film budgets.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Photomatix was also the trademarked name of many of the booths found in public places which took photographs by coin operation.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The Photomatic brand of the booths was manufactured by the International Mutoscope Reel Company of New York City.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Earlier versions took only one photo per coin, and later versions of the booths took a series of photos.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Many of the booths would produce a strip of four photos in exchange for a coin (or coins).
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Some writers have used storyboard type drawings (albeit rather sketchy) for their scripting of comic books, often indicating staging of figures, backgrounds, and balloon placement with instructions to the artist as needed often scribbled in the margins and the dialogue or captions indicated.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] John Stanley and Carl Barks (when he was writing stories for the Junior Woodchuck title) are known to have used this style of scripting.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] In Japanese comics, the word "name" (ネーム, *nēmu*; pronounced [neːmɯ]) is used for rough manga storyboards.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Storyboards used for planning advertising campaigns such as corporate video production, commercials, a proposal or other business presentations intended to convince or compel to action are known as presentation boards.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Presentation boards will generally be a higher quality render than shooting boards as they need to convey expression, layout, and mood.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Modern ad agencies and marketing professionals will create presentation boards either by hiring a storyboard artist to create hand-drawn illustrated frames or often use sourced photographs to create a loose narrative of the idea they are trying to sell.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Storyboards can also be used to visually understand the consumer experience by mapping out the customer's journey brands can better identify potential pain points and anticipate their emerging needs.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The initial storyboard may be as simple as slide titles on Post-It notes, which are then replaced with draft presentation slides as they are created.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Storyboards also exist in accounting in the ABC System activity-based costing (ABC) to develop a detailed process flowchart which visually shows all activities and the relationships among activities.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] They are used in this way to measure the cost of resources consumed, identify and eliminate non-value-added costs, determine the efficiency and effectiveness of all major activities, and identify and evaluate new activities that can improve future performance.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] A "quality storyboard" is a tool to help facilitate the introduction of a quality improvement process into an organization.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] "Design comics" are a type of storyboard used to include a customer or other characters into a narrative.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Design comics are most often used in designing websites or illustrating product-use scenarios during design.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Design comics were popularized by Kevin Cheng and Jane Jao in 2006.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Occasionally, architectural studios need a storyboard artist to visualize presentations of their projects.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Usually, a project needs to be seen by a panel of judges and nowadays it's possible to create virtual models of proposed new buildings, using advanced computer software to simulate lights, settings, and materials.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Clearly, this type of work takes time – and so the first stage is a draft in the form of a storyboard, to define the various sequences that will subsequently be computer-animated.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Storyboards are now becoming more popular with novelists.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Because most novelists write their stories by scenes rather than chapters, storyboards are useful for plotting the story in a sequence of events and rearranging the scenes accordingly.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] More recently the term *storyboard* has been used in the fields of web development, software development, and instructional design to present and describe, in written, interactive events as well as audio and motion, particularly on user interfaces and electronic pages.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Storyboarding is used in software development as part of identifying the specifications for a particular set of software.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] During the specification phase, screens that the software will display are drawn, either on paper or using other specialized software, to illustrate the important steps of the user experience.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The storyboard is then modified by the engineers and the client while they decide on their specific needs.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The reason why storyboarding is useful during software engineering is that it helps the user understand exactly how the software will work, much better than an abstract description.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] It is also cheaper to make changes to a storyboard than an implemented piece of software.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] An example is the Storyboards system for designing GUI apps for iOS and macOS.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Storyboards are used in linguistic fieldwork to elicit spoken language.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] An informant is usually presented with a simplified graphical depiction of a situation or story, and asked to describe the depicted situation, or to re-tell the depicted story.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The speech is recorded for linguistic analysis.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] One advantage of using storyboards is that it allows (in film and business) the user to experiment with changes in the storyline to evoke stronger reaction or interest.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Flashbacks, for instance, are often the result of sorting storyboards out of chronological order to help build suspense and interest.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Another benefit of storyboarding is that the production can plan the movie in advance.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] In this step, things like the type of camera shot, angle, and blocking of characters are decided.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The process of visual thinking and planning allows a group of people to brainstorm together, placing their ideas on storyboards and then arranging the storyboards on the wall.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] This fosters more ideas and generates consensus inside the group.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Modern digital storyboard tools also streamline this process by allowing teams to collaborate remotely, automatically organize panels, and even generate visuals using AI.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Storyboards for films are created in a multiple-step process.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] They can be created by hand drawing or digitally on a computer.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] If drawing by hand, the first step is to create or download a storyboard template.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] These look much like a blank comic strip, with space for comments and dialogue.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Some directors sketch thumbnails directly in the script margins.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] These storyboards get their name because they are rough sketches not bigger than a thumbnail.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] For some motion pictures, thumbnail storyboards are sufficient.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] However, some filmmakers rely heavily on the storyboarding process.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] If a director or producer wishes, more detailed and elaborate storyboard images are created.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] These can be created by professional storyboard artists by hand on paper or digitally by using 2D storyboarding programs.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Some software applications even supply a stable of storyboard-specific images making it possible to quickly create shots that express the director's intent for the story.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] These boards tend to contain more detailed information than thumbnail storyboards and convey more of the mood for the scene.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] These are then presented to the project's cinematographer who achieves the director's vision.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Finally, if needed, 3D storyboards are created (called 'technical previsualization').
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The advantage of 3D storyboards is they show exactly what the film camera will see using the lenses the film camera will use.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] The disadvantage of 3D is the amount of time it takes to build and construct the shots.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] 3D storyboards can be constructed using 3D animation programs or digital puppets within 3D programs.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Some programs have a collection of low-resolution 3D figures which can aid in the process.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Some 3D applications allow cinematographers to create "technical" storyboards which are optically-correct shots and frames.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] While technical storyboards can be helpful, optically-correct storyboards may limit the director's creativity.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] In classic motion pictures such as Orson Welles' *Citizen Kane* and Alfred Hitchcock's *North by Northwest*, the director created storyboards that were initially thought by cinematographers to be impossible to film.
[src:uikit-ios/storyboard] Such innovative and dramatic shots had "impossible" depth of field and angles where there was "no room for the camera" – at least not until creative solutions were found to achieve the ground-breaking shots that the director had envisioned.
